# AES-XTS IEEE Std 1619-2007 Annex B + OpenSSL CTS partial-length KAT
#
# Tests the pure-Simple AES-XTS implementation in src/os/crypto/aes_xts.spl
# against published reference vectors. Two independent sources cross-checked
# byte-for-byte before transcription:
#   - Linux kernel crypto/testmgr.h (aes_xts_tv_template) — IEEE 1619 TV1-TV4
#     plus IEEE 1619 TV10 (AES-256, sector 0xff, 512 bytes).
#   - OpenSSL test/recipes/30-test_evp_data/evpciph_aes_common.txt — same
#     IEEE 1619 vectors plus a 17-byte CTS partial-length AES-128 vector.
#
# Coverage matrix:
#   * TV1 (AES-128, klen=32, len=32, sector=0): all-zero key/PT — exercises
#     the basic XEX path with a degenerate tweak (k1==k2==0 violates IEEE 1619
#     §5.1 in production, but is the canonical TV1 used by both Linux and
#     OpenSSL test suites).
#   * TV2 (AES-128, klen=32, len=32, sector=0x3333333333): non-trivial sector
#     index — exercises sector-index little-endian encoding and AES_K2 tweak
#     derivation.
#   * TV3 (AES-128, klen=32, len=32, sector=0x3333333333): different keys, same
#     sector — guards against key-mixing bugs.
#   * TV4 (AES-128, klen=32, len=512, sector=0): 32 full blocks — stresses
#     GF(2^128) tweak doubling (alpha = x in F_2[x]/(x^128+x^7+x^2+x+1)) across
#     31 successive multiplications.
#   * TV5 (AES-256, klen=64, len=512, sector=0xff): full AES-256 key schedule,
#     32 blocks — validates the inline _aes256_expand_key path against
#     rt_aes_decrypt_block_with_expanded.
#   * CTS-17 (AES-128, klen=32, len=17, sector=0x123456789a): IEEE 1619 §5.4
#     ciphertext-stealing path with one full block plus a 1-byte partial.
#     Catches CTS byte-ordering bugs that round-trip alone misses.
#
# Each vector also exercises decrypt (KAT inverse) and round-trip
# (encrypt then decrypt = identity) — round-trip alone is necessary-not-
# sufficient (a wrong CTS byte order can still round-trip).
#
# Byte-equality assertions fire under interpreter mode post-W11-A. AES block
# primitives route through rt_aes{128,256}_encrypt_block_pure (W13-A fix,
# returns cipher; the older _into variants silently dropped the result under
# interpreter mode — see doc/08_tracking/bug/rt_aes_encrypt_block_into_interpreter_arc_2026-05-02.md).
#
# KNOWN BLOCKER (2026-05-02 W17-B): All assertions currently fail with
#   "runtime: rt_aes128_encrypt_block_pure expects an array of integers"
# under interpreter mode. Root cause is NOT in this spec or in
# src/os/crypto/aes_xts.spl — it is in the upstream
# src/os/crypto/aes128_gcm.spl::aes128_encrypt_block wrapper, which builds
# the round-key arg via `key.push(_u8_at(round_keys, i))` where `_u8_at`
# returns `u8`. Under interpreter mode this produces a `Value::Array(Vec<U8>)`,
# but `expect_byte_array` in src/compiler_rust/compiler/src/interpreter_extern/simd.rs
# (line 47) only accepts `Value::Int` elements.
# The aes128_gcm_nist_vectors_spec / aes_cmac_rfc4493_kat_spec / aes256_gcm
# KATs all fail with the same error today (2026-05-02) for the same reason.
# SHA-256 / SHA-512 KATs pass because their fixture path uses bare-int push
# (`out.push(0x61)`) and never wraps via `.to_u8()`.
# Fix is upstream of W17-B's disjoint scope; tracked in
#   doc/08_tracking/bug/aes_extern_expect_byte_array_u8_reject_2026-05-02.md
# When the upstream fix lands, every assertion in this file should fire
# byte-exact against the IEEE 1619 vectors transcribed below.
#
# Sources:
#   IEEE Std 1619-2007 Annex B (canonical XTS-AES test vectors)
#     - mirrored in https://github.com/torvalds/linux/blob/master/crypto/testmgr.h
#   OpenSSL evpciph_aes_common.txt
#     - https://github.com/openssl/openssl/blob/master/test/recipes/30-test_evp_data/evpciph_aes_common.txt

use std.spipe.*
use os.crypto.aes_xts.{aes128_xts_encrypt_sector, aes128_xts_decrypt_sector, aes256_xts_encrypt_sector, aes256_xts_decrypt_sector}

